column70: I have taken courses in general forestry and regularly seek out management tips and helpful advice from websites that deal with small scale, sustainable forestry.  I have written my own management plans, and review and update them every year. I also monitor very closely the age and general health of each stand in the woodlot and make decisions based on a number of factors such as market conditions and demand, availability of time to do management work, etc.
column71: I have increased the share of natural regeneration.
column102: Severe snowstorm in 2013 destroyed 80% of my coniferous stands. We carried out a harvest of the the logs that were able to be salvaged so that it would reduce the chance of forest fires by reducing the fuel load, and to reduce the chance of insect infestation in the remaining stand. Otherwise I would have harvested eventually, but only as market conditions were favorable.
column111: Climate change models in our area seem to indicate warmer, wetter winters which would reduce the risk of drought by recharging soil moisture during spring thaw.  However, the models also show the risk of hotter drier summers.  This would result in a tendency to increase the hardwoods rather than softwoods because they have less tendency to burn (fewer flammable resins in the hardwoods such as Trembling Aspen)
column149:
I have focused much more on increasing access to my woodlot using a network of trails for 2 reasons:  1. to increase access to forest fire equipment in the event of a fire, and to act as a fireguard.   2. to make it easier to monitor the general health of the trees in the woodlot.
I also try and maintain high stand density to prevent 'windthrow' since we seem to have more weather events that bring high winds.
column172: I think the coniferous trees in our woodlot are more prone to forest fires, windstorms (lateral roots make them tip over easier) as well as drought mainly because the sandy soil in our woodlot does not retain soil moisture very well. We've had 2 dry years back to back and they are showing signs of stress already (such as yellowing of the needles)
column185: Provincial forestry departments should set the guidelines for enhanced management practices to mitigate risks to woodlots caused by climate change (ie best management practices)  Woodlot owner organizations could then become the delivery agency, to help educate other woodlot owners about sustainable forestry practices in the context of climate change. Landscape level management would become critical to this approach so that, for instance, neglected woodlot don't build up a huge fuel load which can increase the risk of massive fires in the region.

column208:
Our woodlot is 160 kilometers from our principal residence. I would love to spend more time there, but the cost of fuel is making it more difficult.  I revisit the management plan and have kept a journal since 1986 on the harvests, replanting, and other silviculture work I have done. I would like to leave the woodlot in better shape than when I bought it.  I have created a network of access trails that allows me to monitor any stands that seem to have an issue, and to allow harvesting equipment to enter the stands without creating collateral damage to the trees.
Our woodlot is a mixed woods forest, but in the last decade, it has been the coniferous trees that have been damaged by severe weather.

column42: We originally bought the lots as 5 brothers. Three are now deceased, leaving 2 brothers and one widow. Two partners were bought out after death. We have over the years  harvested about 50% and replanted as the stands were mature and were recommended for removal. We also have a gravel deposit on the property  which helped with road construction and the resulting pit provided a nice duck's unlimited pond  and a source of water for fire fighting. We have thinned a 20 acre stand of maple for maple syrup production and that has been running for about 12 years. We have decided not to do any more large harvests as we feel carbon capture is far more important and we can continue with thining and removing unwanted species  to generally improve the woodlots and provide firewood.

column149: Interesting for me is the notion of adapting to climate change as opposed to trying to slow it down.  The logging industry is a legitimate industry that must do its part to regenerate forests.  I am pragmatic about climate change.  Slow it down when possible, adapt when necessary.  I see this process as two parallel lines that intersect frequently. I expect governments to do their job to regulate industries who have a direct and indirect impact on climate change. I am not an ideologue and I have zero patience with activists.  I will make full use of the expertise around me especially the OWA.  I am going to invite them to visit my woodlot.
column172: I am so angry at the polarized views on this issue and it is made worse by social media and perceived breakdown of the trust between the general public and scientists.  I have always said "Show Me the Data!"  But know I'm not sure that I trust the data.  Many scientists are activists for a particular outcome and  that is not science!!!!!  When I hear "we have to save the planet or we will all die". I close my ears.  when I hear "There is no such thing as climate change" etc.. I close my ears.  I no longer trust the non profit environmental org industry. Now I say "show me the money!"  Nor do I trust forest and petroleum companies who say they are helping the environment.  To them I say" "Show me the unbiased, no conflict of interest, independent third party research".  Its a sad place to be.
column185: NOT environmental groups.  They have become way too big and they exist to keep themselves going.  They are bloated.  They have agendas that are not always congruent with what they say they believe.  Not Big companies who profit for the same reasons.   I see these two groups as complicit. I believe that woodlot owners, fed and prov. governments must lead.  Consult with the above but this must be in the hands of elected officials who interpret good data to make their decisions.

column185: any initiatives for adaptation to climate change related to private forests need to be joint done by committee of government and private landowners. this does not mean and should not include executive directors of private landowner organizations, not include foresters unless they are landowners themselves and rely on their woodlots for part of their livelihood, not include industrial woodlot owners or foresters that work for them, definitely no NGOs. the reason for this position is private woodlots belong to the private woodlot owner and society should have no input into how practices and changes are made to adapt woodlots, government needs to be at the table to provide funding and deliver programs once developed. column42: Je suis propriétaire de 350 acres forestiers dont 80 en plantation à forte croissance, le reste est régie que par des coupes sélectives, peu ou pas de coupe à blanc. Les 100 acres restants sont dévolus au pacage et récolte de foin par mon voisin. Depuis 40 ans que je suis propriétaire, il y a eu retour des cerfs de Virginie, orignaux, ours noirs, dindon, salamandre de diverses espèces et autres. Des plantes sont aussi revenues entre autre du cypripède acaule (sabot de la vierge). J'ai une cèdrière mature d'environ 40 acres où j'ai cessé la coupe et le drainage pour garder un milieu humide, les grenouilles ( peu ) sont revenues même une espèce forestière. Des canards nichent au printemps.  Je suis sous régie du syndicat forestier. J'ai environ 100 acres en érablière sous régie biologique. Mon fils reprendra ma terre et progressera avec la même philosophie.
column70: Je suis la cinquième génération à exploiter ces terres et une grande partie de mon érablière est entaillée depuis plus de 150 ans, on peur appeler ça du développement durable. Mon fils me succédera, c'est très important pour moi.  J'accorde une grande importance à la beauté de ma terre et au développement durable.

column112: Le changement climatique est une notion plus théorique qu'autre chose pour moi. Même si je ne réfute pas les changements climatiques, je n'y accorde pas beaucoup d'importance. Par contre ma gestion forestière et la croissance des plantations et autres surfaces boisées contribue, selon les scientifiques, à la captation du carbone. Même si ce n'est pas mon objectif premier, tout ça est un tout et ça contribue positivement à l'environnement.

column149: Ce sera mon fils qui dans quelques années orientera la gestion forestière vers des normes plus avancées comme le changement climatique. Il sera capable de le faire parce qu'il aura une marge financière qui ne l'obligera pas à exploiter au maximum pour payer la terre.
column172: Quand j'était petit et mon père un paysan, le lac de mon village puait, les égoûts des maisons dans mon rang se déversait dans le fossé et rejoignait ruisseau et rivière. Les cerfs de Virginie étaient très râre, pas d'orignal, d'ours, plus de grenouille ni de salamandre excepté les petites dans la terre noire des forêts. Chaque maison avait son dépotoir à l'orée de la forêt et les ferrailles rouillaient en arrière de la grange. De la maison, on voyait tout autour, aucune forêt mature ou peu, tout était en culture ou jachère parce que la pauvreté prévalait, mon père devait exploiter durement son environnement pour survivre. Les choses ont heureusement changé et changeront encore, j'ai fait mon bout de chemin, je laisse la suite aux nouvelles générations.

column70: We have owned our current woodlot (which is combined with a lakefront cottage) since 1976. This woodlot and several previously owned woodlots have  been continually managed for major objectives of environmental protection, investment and family recreation and  the lesser secondary objective of harvesting woodlot products for personal use and sale of sawlogs from a couple of selection improvement logging cuts, firewood from windfalls and maple syrup. I am not formally trained in forestry but have been long time very active in woodlot associations, volunteer work in land stewardship council and conservation authority and relevant association with forestry experts and other forest owners and extensive reading on forestry subjects, all of which I feel has qualified me to prepare/maintain my own management plan and manage my forest mainly myself according to the above objectives.
column71: I have increased the share of natural regeneration.
column102: Our grandson, who is an environmental scientist, and very interested in the woodlot, is becoming much more involved in the woodlot management with my blessing as I am decreasing my activities now that I am in my mid 80s. He recently suggested leaving the 1/3 of the woodlot fronting the lake as a protected forest  and the plan has been accordingly modified. Also  about 10% of the forest of upland compartment suffered major mortality (prob. due to drought) of the predominant red oak therein about 15 years ago; so the compartment was since cleared of the dead trees and undesirable undergrowth; several hundred white pines were planted and competition has continued to be cleared to allow the pines and regenerating oak to thrive. The remaining 90%  is mixed age hardwood/conifer forest and continues thriving with minimal intervention with many mature stems up to 100 ft. tall and up to 3 ft. in diameter.
column112: An upland compartment comprising 10% 0f the woodlot, that suffered extensive oak mortality, has since been been cleared and annually the competition of regenerating pine and oak has been cleared of competition. A 1/3 portion of the woodlot, comprising the  lake front portion, has been designated a protected area. Apart from these 2 recent changes, the long standing objectives and plans remain the same because they have been audited and passed  for adherence  to FSC principles and Ontario MFTIP inspections and therefore I considered the management to be in line with combatting climate change. The forest stand and wildlife continue to thrive and the water quality of the  adjacent lake (of which our woodlot comprises 1/4 of the lake boundary) continues to be one of best in the municipality.
column149: I believe a continuing thriving forest with a diversity of species and stem sizes, avoiding pesticides and fertilizers unless direly needed, managing a forest according to FSC principles, nurturing wildlife, protecting water and air quality and avoiding prescribed burns are all actions that best protect the environment, sequester carbon  and combat climate change. If in future climate change results in a species shift, action can then be taken to introduce suitable replacement species.
column172: Climate change is increased by human activity to some extent but the greater influence is other than man made, such as volcanic activity, solar changes, etc. Climate change has been ongoing on earth since before the time of human existence,  eg there have been  equatorial fossils found in the Arctic. I understand that carbon sequestering as accomplished by trees combats climate change nd is encouraged rather than adding to atmospheric carbon by prescribed burns and heavy logging, clear cutting and eliminating species of trees.
column185: It is most important that governments lead the way by encouraging and if necessary legislating action based on sound scientific evidence to control man made effects of climate change. Then private forest owners, NGOs, forestry professionals and forest certification agencies need to follow suit.

column208: I was raised on a backwoods self-sufficient Manitoba farm just after the 1930s depression, scrounged to save funds to acquire a degree in geological engineering, did surveying and remote geology field work across Canada for several years and spent most of my career in IT field with IBM and federal government. We have lived for 60 years in a city and in mid 1960s started to buy several successive woodlot/recreational properties within 40-100 km of our home for purposes of diversifying investments, family recreational/outdoor/rural activity and secondarily small scale woodlot production for personal use and for sale of such as logs for a log cabin I built, firewood and maple syrup. I did many years of environmental related volunteer work with several woodlot associations, stewardship council and conservation authority and learned much from the experience and contacts. I had several woodlot related articles published by Ont. Woodlot Assoc. (I can provide copies if of interest or relevant to survey). We won an international award for forest stewardship. Our woodlot was one of first private woodlots to be certified in Canada. Our whole family has much used/enjoyed/benefitted from our woodlot/rec. properties in many ways and our descendants much look forward to continuing the activity.

column42: J'ai aménagé un sentier de raquettes pour en profiter l'hiver et il y a un camp forestier pour se réchauffer.  Au printemps, une petite érablière artisanale de moins de 100 entailles.  Pour le reste du temps, je fais du nettoyage et je reboise des petits arbres tels que des feuillus nobles uniquement.  Une partie des plants provient de pépinières avec le regroupement forestier (érable à sucre) et l'autre partie d'une quantité importante de feuillus nobles que je produits dans mon jardin à l'aide de semences récoltées dans des parcs de la région de Montréal. Dans ces essences, il y a du chêne bicolore, rouge, pédonculé, blanc, à gros fruits, caryer ovale, cordiforme, glabre, cerisier tardif, noyer noir, noyer cendré en grande quantité mais il y a aussi du chicot du Canada, micocoulier occidental, ginkgo biloba, marronnier d'Ohio.  Avec le réchauffement climatique, je pense pouvoir réussir à faire pousser ces essences qui se retrouvent au-delà de leur zone climatique.  Ce boisé a été acquis en 2017 et il avait été surexploité par le propriétaire précédent, ce qui me permet de le nettoyer et de le reboiser à ma guise. Il est situé en zone 4b dans la municipalité de Notre-Dame-du-Mont-Carmel en Mauricie dans la province de Québec.
column70: L'acquisition d'une terre à bois est un projet qui date de mon enfance car mes parents ont des terres. Et bien comme je le mentionnais dans la section précédente, le fait de planter des essences au-delà de leur zone climatique fera à long terme une forêt probablement unique dans la région.

column102: L'ensemble de mon lot est surmature et surtout de composition résineuse.  Je réalise des coupes finales car les coupes partielles amènent beaucoup de chablis.  Suite à la parution d'articles scientifiques, je veux plus de diversité pour la production de bois et pour faire face à des changements climatiques.  J'ai reboisé des parcelles de récolte totale à des densités moindre en résineux pour avoir une forêt mixte plutôt qu'en plantations pures.  En outre, je réalise des coupes totales par trouées pour contrôler la lumière et minimiser l'apparition de framboisier.
column149: Je vois mal le lien entre les assurances et les changements climatiques !
column172: Mon lot sera affecté à 100 % par les changements climatiques à divers niveaux.  Je remarque une présence accru du hêtre en régénération, même s'il est plutôt absent en terme d'arbres adulte sur mon lot et à proximité.  Aussi, nous venons de connaître 2 printemps hâtifs secs.  La croissance de mes jeunes plantations semblent en souffrir.  Il y a eu aussi des gels printaniers sur 2 années consécutives.  Les jeunes pousses annuelles d'épinette blanche et de sapin beaumier ont gelé.  Enfin, je remarque de plus en plus de sapins matures qui sèchent debout sans raison apparente.

column42: Le boisé contient 10 ha de plantations âgées entre 30 et 40 ans. Des éclaircies commerciales ont lieu dans ces plantations lorsque requises. Les peuplements forestiers naturels sont soit résineux, mélangés ou feuillus. Les feuillus âgés sont issus d'une érablière à bouleau jaune en dépérissement. Présentement, des efforts sont consentis à la récolte des sapins et des épinettes mûres et des éclaircies dans les plantations de résineux. Du reboisement a lieu dans les zones affectées par des châblis.
column70: Je possède le boisé en co-propriété avec mon épouse. Je suis un passionné de la forêt ayant une formation en foresterie. Je me sens chez moi lorsque je suis en forêt. Présentement, j'utilise des pièces de bois provenant des arbres que j'ai planté dans les années 80. D'ailleurs, le bois ayant servi à la construction de l'abri forestier, situé sur le lot boisé, provient de mon boisé. J'ai récolté les arbres, les ai fait scié et mis au séchage naturel pendant quelques années avant de m'en servir pour la construction. Je retire beaucoup de satisfaction à utiliser le bois d'oeuvre provenant de mes plantations.

column70: J'ai acheté la terre de mes parents pour une continuité familiale. Nous en sommes à la 8e génération. Avec mon père, nous faisions environ 15 cordes de bois de pulpe par année. Nous avons cessé il y a environ 8 ans. Mon père est décédé l'an passée. Je suis en réflexion sur la façon d'exploiter la forêt du fait que les papetières n'utilisent plus le bois en 4 pieds. Si je choisi de continuer l'exploitation moi-même, je devrai investir pour m'équiper. Je suis à la retraite du travail et les revenus potentiels de l'exploitation forestière ne me sont pas essentiels. L'apparence de la forêt suite à une récolte par une entreprise forestière m'inquiète beaucoup. Ma réflexion se poursuit.

Pour ma part, je ne crois pas au changement climatique en lien avec le CO².
Je crois plutôt que l'humain a extrêmement modifié la capacité de la terre à se tempérer elle-même. Le plus gros problème est le nombre de mètres carrés d'asphalte, de surfaces de béton et des systèmes de drainage sous-terrain qui empêche l'eau de prénetrer le sol. C'est pas sorcier à comprendre, prenez la température de votre entrée de maison en pleine canicule et comparez à une surface de gazon ou de gravier.   Le constat n'est pas dur à faire. Mettez ça à l'échelle mondiale. Cumulez tout les °C supplémentaires accumulé et réfléchis par les mètres carrés d'asphalte vous n'aurez pas à chercher de midi à 14h pour comprendre d'où vient le réchauffement climatique.

column102: C'est le lot que je vais avec mon grand père depuis 40 ans.  Ce dernier ne s'en servait que pour produire son bois de chauffage sans en faire aucune autre exploitation. De plus ayant re marqué le dépérissement de sapin; j'ai decide d'en prélevé un certain nombre annuellement tant qu'il a une certaine valeur commerciale et il sert aussi a la combustion pour la production acéricole.
column149: Le changement climatique est une chose normale.  Avec un certain recul, on peut voir qu'il y a des millions d'années nous étions dans une aire glacière avec un réchauffement progressif.  Or je suis conscient que l'activité humaine a amené une accélération démesuré de ce changement.  Depuis 40 ans on peut observer un changement au niveau ornithologique et aussi au niveau des insectes.  Je crois donc que les essences de nos forets boréales sont amenées à changer.  C'est pourquoi je laisse la nature s'adapter par elle meme; mais en lui donnant un petit coup de main en évitant la prolification de certaine espèces envahissantes et en laissant le plus de chance à certaines essences plus malmenées tel le frêne.

column172: Climate change is evident in our woodlot as warmer winters, drier summers (high certainty), increased precip (probably) and increased pests (maybe).  I believe climate change is already affecting 100% of the ecosystem on thew woodlot though at this point the effects are not yet severe
column185:
Increased use of wood products for buildings, energy and feedstocks for other products is going to be part of climate change solutions. so if anything incentoives may push towards managing more intensively for timber.

Regulations may be part of the solution however small woodlot owners don't have a lot of capacity or financial resources to follow complex regulations. At least initially the focus needs to be on educating the entire industry (big forestry, government agencies, woodlot owners) on what climate change best practices are (which vary by ecozone across Canada).  After these best practices are widely understood and agreed on then it may be time for some science based regulations.

column70:
In my woodlot’s township, there are no tree cutting bylaws and logging is a huge part of the industry in the local area. I purchased the property to preserve a piece of beautiful land, and I take pride in stewarding it. It’s a give and take relationship when owning a woodlot. We heal each other, and the forest teaches adults and children many things. It is my goal to build a forest school, wilderness and culture centre on my MFTIP managed woodlot so the locale can learn about forests and make informed choices when managing their private lots as well. 
Another part of the land stewardship is that this land is unceded Algonquin territory, and it means a great deal to me to preserve the traditions and culture of the Indigenous peoples who lived and thrived on these lands that were taken from them by settlers, and exploited for their resources. A common practice I witness every day here. 
Preservation and respect for the land is my priority.

column149: Les réelles effets relatifs aux changements climatiques sont pour l'instant très difficiles à prévoir avec un degré de fiabilité raisonnable. Les propriétaires de boisés ont besoin de beaucoup de liberté pour adapter les décisions en fonction des changements à venir. column42:
A Woodlot in New Brunswick is considered to be 25 acres as defined by NB policy I believe
Our property is 18 acres, but we manage it like a Woodlot and enjoy it like a woodlot . We live on the property . Harvest annual firewood for ourselves. Plant hardwoods , softwoods , develop trails. Tap trees for maple syrup. Hunt deer. We’ve done pre commercial thinning , built ducks unlimited ponds.
column70: I am a forester , and have previously worked in the private Woodlot sector for over 10 years, so I feel I am capable of making my own decisions on Woodlot management. This is not the case for everyone , so others should seek professional advise when necessary. In my time and experience in the private Woodlot sector , I saw many Woodlot owners communicate directly with logging contractors as their first point of contact. Logging contractors need to cut wood for their livelihoods , so owners may not always get the best advise.  I believe other resources for Woodlot owners like professional advise , meetings , research , market information, continuing education , etc is all very beneficial for Woodlot owners and private Woodlot management.
column71: I have increased the share of planting.
column102: Species adaptation , climate change . I’ve introduced more oak on my Woodlot and have planted white pine and hemlock.  I’m releasing red maple and protecting red maple. Cutting my balsam fir, but I also maintain an area of over mature fir for different habitat characteristics and for a “ legacy” area. Pilleated woodpecker enjoy my large fir . The market conditions are not worth harvesting softwood for a mill. They’re better suited to cut and mill the wood yourself
column111: I prefer a hardwood forest, and I’ve been gradually thinning out my balsam fir and inter planting red oak. I’ve sprinkled some white pine and hemlock throughout as well. I’m not managing my Woodlot for a sawmill. I’m also keeping my eye on carbon markets for down the road.

column208: Il est impératif que nos gouvernements s'impliquent davantage (sous formes d'incitation et non d'obligation) dans la gestion de nos forêts autant public que privé. Le soucis de rentabilité ne devrait pas être l'objectif premier dans la gestion de nos forêts mais plutôt de transmettre des valeurs de conservation a nos descendants (futures générations) de façon a ce qu'elles jouissent comme nous des bienfaits que nos forêts apportent en terme de qualité de l'air, de diminution de stress, d'activités (chasse, pêche, randonnées pédestres et autres) qu'on ne retrouvent pas en ville.  Il m'apparaît que les défis du futur pour nos forêts seront énormes (incendie, ouragans, insectes venus d'ailleurs, agrandissement des villes, pollution,etc.). column102: We have a large woodlot with a lot of balsam fir.  Being a short lived species as well as being impacted by climate change, we have a great deal of this species dead or dying in our woodlot.  We were unable to harvest the fir fast enough ourselves to keep up so sold stumpage to larger contractors for a few year.  We weren't happy with really low stumpage rates so recently purchased some more efficient forestry equipment to allow us to harvest it quicker ourselves and do it without having larger clearcuts.   We are doing some small clear cutting as well as shelter wood where it makes sense.
column112: We are somewhat concerned about our small sugarbush operation and what impacts climate change may have on that.  We also have a large percentage of balsam fir stands which tend to regenerate to balsam fir. We are trying to promote more spruce and hardwood growth.
column149: Out woodlots are diverse and somewhat widespread.  So, answers reflect different objectives for different woodlots.  They aren't all managed the same.  We already have a tourism/outfitting part of our business and take wildlife as well as aesthetics into account on some portions of the woodlot.
column172: Ice storms may be the biggest concern on our woodlots as we have seen extensive damage from these storms.  Wind damage in the form of blowdown of trees left standing in shelter wood or seed tree operations is also of concern.

column80: I selected the best seedlings for the site for the current climate and into the reasonable future. I felt it was not reasonable to plant something ie Larch that would thrive in 100 years if it is not going to survive the next 20 years. Therefore I went for “improved” Class A spruce seedlings.
column102: All of the nearby forest fires in central BC motivated us to log the mature forest on the property. Also since we don’t live at the property and we are seeing more and more people “squatting” on private land with a potential for fires.
column112: We plan to keep the carbon credits ourself for the family. The grandkids may sell them, but that would be their decision. The land also has 25 ha of pasture and the neighbor has cattle that “escape” so there is grazing pressure on the seedlings.
column149: I planned to mound and/or disc trench before planting but equipment was not available at the time. It is a wetter site beside wetlands and a lake and the seedlings would have benefited. I don’t do pesticides, Roundup, or fertilizer ever on the site. Now that planting all other work is complete I will be grass seeding this spring on all disturbed soil to reduce erosion impact and invasive weeds. I do not generally believe in introducing foreign plants. Other than extending “range”. Ie Larch in drier sites
column172: When harvesting I switched to a “at the stump” process versus a traditional roadside stroking method. While more expensive, this was to keep the existing Df and pine cones on the site for natural regen in addition to the spruce that was planted at a 1400 per ha density.
column185: I’m not doing what other land owners are doing, I feel I am doing a much better job as a result of personal/professional pride. Leave strips, debris disposal, planting with higher cost seedlings, grass seeding, fencing to try and keep the cattle out, etc.

column42: We are in the boreal forest of far North East Ontario. Our property is 80 acres, 55 forested and mostly upland mixed wood; 40% White Spruce, 20% Trembling Aspen, 20% Balsam Fir, 10% White Birch, 10% Balsam Poplar. The white spruce are a result from 1919 giant fire in our region. So are ~ 100 years old. Some are VERY large and beautiful. A creek flows through our property that has brook trout from time to time, (*in our area they are not faithful to their spawning areas), in this creek. Several beaver families live on this creek on our property. Our home by the road, is in cleared area, former farm lands, although surrounded by wind break which I have planted, mostly white spruce, living fence. The neighbour has forested lot next to us, another 80 acre lot.
column70: Mostly we enjoy the wild lands with moose, bears, wolves, lynx, grouse, snowshoe hare, etc. living in our backyard. I use to take a lot of dead wood for firewood out of the woodlot, but take a lot less now. I love that many of the trees are attaining large size and understand that the old growth forests sequester the most carbon. Many of my neighbours sold their wood off of their lots, so I have an island of old growth forest in a sea of younger forests. I am thinking of slowly picking out large white spruce/aspen for sawlogs, but just as I need wood for construction etc. I am a Forestry Technician/Fish & Wildlife Technician retired from the Ministry of Natural Resources and Forests, so I am "managing" the forests as need be.
column71: I have increased the share of planting.
column80: I plant for permaculture and food production for humans and wildlife.
column102: As most of my neighbours harvested their lands for $, we resisted even though we could have used the money for our kids college. I am glad we did not harvest our forest, as we have a Jewel of Old Growth Forest surrounded by young forests. All kinds of wildlife utilize our forests. No changes have taken place since 2010 other than taking less dead wood for fire wood, although I do take some dead wood for a food forest and haskap plantation I have planted on the cleared front of the property.
column111: Our Municipality which has a lot of forested lands want to get into Carbon Credit programs, and as such will also need private forested land to achieve their goals, which could produce $ for us personally and for our community.
column112: No major changes... perhaps a lessening of harvesting firewood which mostly was already standing dead trees, not green.
column149: I believe our 55 acres of old growth forests are very insulated from many climate changes and pests. As some trees die, others fill the canopy. I have added more southerly species in some trials and have successfully planted black walnut in the understory in zone 2! This also works with many other more southerly native tree species from zone 3 and even zone 4. I have successfully planted bur oak, apple trees and butternut in the understory of mature mixed wood forests, in areas where other trees have fallen etc...
column172: Climate change is also an opportunity. We are in the Great Clay Belt, and so far the Ministry of Agriculture has been spot on in stating that we will have more rain, and also more drought. How is this possible? Rain events will be greater, but heat events bring weather to drought conditions much quicker as well.  In the mature old growth mixed wood forests this is not an issue, as the robust leaf and woody litter keep moisture in not allowing it to evaporate as quickly. And we know the old growth forest trees also aid the growth of younger trees using the mycelium layers to aid smaller trees in need.  The issue becomes acute when clear cuts are employed, since the tree plantations are far far more susceptible to the extremes in weather and climate change in general. The opportunity part is to be able to diversify, and add useful tree species such as food trees, and wildlife trees. Cherries, nuts and fruit trees ash trees etc (*we are out of the range of bronze ash borer beetle and still have extreme cold winters) are just a few of these examples which I know I can underplant due to my trials. So maintain old growth, and harvest only diseased/dead trees and use the openings as an opportunity to plant more southerly species.
column178: permaculture ideology is key to success. Also think agro-forestry.  I have taken many online permaculture courses and am able to manage my forest to great success.
column185: I think the worst thing to do is add more regulation, other than to leave more old growth forests which really aids all the forests. The best thing to do is make more courses available with real science on how to change management of forests to adapt to climate change. It is an opportunity as much as it is a problem. Diversification and adding species will help make a forest more insulated from climate change. Clear cutting practices used by most companies and MNDMNRF are part of the problem and not the solution. Wildlife and Forests can become far more robust and insulated from climate change if it is done right, and not just the profit of logging considered.
column187: Big Trees and Old Growth Forest Facebook Page
column204: Retired
column208: Although retired I have been asked to provide education on our native natural forests to different school groups, including high school. I am also involved and an active member of our Community Forest Committee.  We are fighting the MNDMNRF (the Natural Resources and Forests Section) to leave larger treed buffers on all our lakes, rivers, streams and wetlands within our Municipality. The NRF is not leaving enough old growth forest, and their buffers (Areas of Concern), along all waterways is far too small for meaningful wildlife habitat and to allow old growth forest to be maintained. Example 30m buffers are too thin for our winds and most do not remain wind fast, and blow down. In many instances the NRF allows harvest companies to harvest right up to waterways!!  I cannot make this up!!  I do not believe it is in the benefit of the forest at all! They say they are trying to mimic wildfire. But I had worked forest fire fighting for many years and the actual amount of times fire burns right up to shorelines is actually very rare!!  So for our community we want larger buffers left so cottagers and home owners can enjoy the forests and old growth forests which are a real rarity!  There are not enough old trees and old growth forests left on the landscape!  Profits are all the NRF and  Logging companies are thinking about..natural forests and old growth forests be damned!

column42: Ma parcelle de 10 acres est n'a pas été récolté de puis, j'estime, environ 100 ans alors que celle de 90 acres, adjacente, a été récoltée en 1975.  Cette dernière inclue environ 25 % de terre humide. J'ai un plan d'aménagement pour cette dernière et me limite à y faire quelques sentiers pour y faire des randonnées en toute saison. Ma famille ( enfants et petits enfants ) y font des sorties de plaisir, d'observation et identification de la faune. J'y récolte un peu de bois de chauffage ( 3 cordes par an environ ) pour la création de sentier. Mes plans sont de garder cette forêt tel quel ( à l'exception des sentiers que j'ai fait ) pour maintenir la biodiversité présente.  Ma forêt de 90 acres est un corridor  faunique  important entre l'immense Forêt Larose et les forêts à l'ouest de celle-ci.
column70: Bon, étant biologiste, j'ai toujours ( et ma famille ) été intéressé et fasciné par les sciences naturelles, et beaucoup plus maintenant à la retraite ! Ce n'est que depuis une dizaine d'années que je me suis intéressé sérieusement à l'importance des arbres et forêts, pour le maintien de la biodiversité, la filtration d'eau et d'air ainsi que la captation du CO2. En 2010, je me suis joint à une association de propriétaires de boisés de l'est de l'Ontario (Boisés Est) et assisté à nombreuses sessions d'informations et d'ateliers sur les bonnes gestions des forêts. Éventuellement, j'ai organisé ces rencontres, rencontré des professionnels en foresterie et devenu Président de l'Association, et suis toujours membre actif. Je consulte donc ces professionnels pour ma prise de décision pour la bonne gestion de ma forêt.

column111: Oh quel question! Je ne vois pas d' "opportunité" mais plutôt un moyen, par l'entremise de la captation du carbone par les forêts, de palier, ou réduire un certain pourcentage de gaz à effet de serre qui cause le réchauffement de notre petite planète!  La compensation financière à l'horizon pour les propriétaire forestiers sera, d'après moi, plus un outil de sensibilisation à la population de l'importance des forêts que le bénéfice financier pour les propriétaires de boisés. Il faudra en premier et rapidement, changer ( et éduquer ) nos concitoyens à consommer moins ( qui a besoin d'un camion et ou VUS tout les jours ... ) et plus intelligemment ( isolation des maisons - a-t-on besoin de 5000 pieds carrés - édifices industriels - transport en commun efficaces etc. ). En fait, l' "opportunité" est plutôt une occasion ( pressante ! ) d'apprendre et changer nos comportements.  Sinon, on sait bien ce qui est en vue!

column185:
Private forests present an opportunity that is quite different from publicly-held land and as such should not be treated in the same way that public lands. The latter are managed as government preserves and nominally as public trusts. I believe that private forests allow for diversification and launches of new ideas at the micro level. Smaller initiatives can be implemented; for example, as I have noted here, there is a local interest all along the St. Lawrence River and into the Niagara region of growing cold hardy varieties of fruits and nuts which have never before been grown in Canada. This has been happening completely naturally in little nature groups and back gardens. Eg I have heard of citrus cultivars which will grow in Ontario. Private forests allow for smaller, bespoke projects which will invite community interest and increase local pride and enterprise.

Private forests can be voluntarily managed as a natural resource with access granted to the public in limited ways as a contribution to community health and communal education, along with local production of rarities such as truffles, wild garlic, wild strawberries, forest mushrooms, fiddleheads etc. These types of efforts have already been long evident in the local culture but could be intensified. The participation of private landowners in such initiatives is already established in local woodland trails. Some trails cross private properties but are accessed by the public.

column70: In May of 1972, the day I graduated from University, I found a 13" black walnut tree on a fence line on our farm.  Nobody believed me.  "it has to be a butternut.  Walnuts don't grow that far north."  I persevered and proved that black walnuts were growing in our woodlot after the previous owner had logged it in 1965.  The squirrels planted nuts from three old black walnut trees on a fence line.  I decided that black walnuts would be my retirement project, and they have served me well.
column71: I have increased the share of planting.
column102:
We had an 11th anniversary reunion in our woodlot in 2021 and the members of the Leeds Stewardship Council included a forestry guy who told me if I didn't cut my diseases beeches out of the woodlot right away, the maples would be lost to stunted beech sprouting everywhere.  The logger took out everything Martin Streit marked for cutting, and that left a lot of space in a ten acre tract.  I spent two weeks last fall teaching myself and a cohort of Grey squirrels how to plant black walnuts.  My crew and I moved about forty, five gallon pails full of nuts.  I believe they planted a good number of them, and I learned to keep the caches away from red squirrels and chipmunks.
Why black walnuts?  Beech are dying.  Ash are dying.  Walnuts thrive in the improving climate of Leeds County.  I give away a lot of nuts to farmers to replace their ash.  With thousand cankers disease in the southern states and BWs marching north into Eastern Ontario, I figured that planting 15 acres of seeds from local trees would be a good idea.  I sold my first tree this year to a furniture factory for $3000.  Nobody believed I could do it, especially the foresters.  I have several dozen more I can harvest whenever I feel the need, though I like to watch them grow.
column111: As I have said before in this survey, I retired from a career in education to grow black walnut trees.  They are doing well, but the trees planted in 2005, while showing promise and producing nuts, are very much a speculative investment at this point.  On the other hand, the black walnuts in the stand which began in 1965 are now quite marketable.  A 60 year-old tree produced a bit over 1000 bd feet of lumber when sold at farm gate.  I did assist the buyer and the sawing contractor with my tractor, but this tree and 2000 feet of basswood logs became revenue for the farm.  The basswood was all that was left from the improvement cut which cleared out the dying beech.  They went for firewood, the logs sawed up and split and loaded into a dump trailer by a very persistent guy about my age who became a good friend.  I won't have a big cut like that again for a long time, but I now have a good logging contractor if I want to take out any more walnut logs.  My walnuts had little trouble with gypsy moths last year, and they normally grow like weeds.  Squirrels spread them and they are better at planting successful seedlings than I am.

column149: The reason I don't plan to thin my old-growth forest is because I just completed a major improvement cut.  200 cords of beech firewood off to market.  Since the snow allowed access, I have put 16 hours on my chipper dealing with limbs from walnut trees I have pruned to encourage growth into logs for market.  I bought a pole saw to deal with larger branches.  I have also cleared and chipped the branches from pine trees to make space for young BWs growing tall and straight in their shelter.  I'm looking for veneer logs from these 4 to 6" saplings. The pines will protect them from the wind until they fill out strong enough to resist the wind on their own.  I knew I had to rely on coyotes to protect my trees from rodents and deer, but this year I have actively recruited Grey squirrels to help with planting.  With a trail camera I was able to learn a lot about their thinking, and I believe Greys are useful to the farmer.
column172: When I grew up in the 60's farmers grew corn for insilage.  Only rarely could a farmer produce seed corn because there weren't enough growing days in our seasons.  Now corn is harvested for the grain and only rarely for forage.  The growing season is at least two weeks longer in our area than it was in the 60's.  In my woodlot walnuts could only grow in a microclimate on a southern slope, sheltered by a ten-acre forest.  That was in 1966.  Now walnuts grow like weeds anywhere on the property that squirrels plant them, and they thrive where they couldn't grow before.  The trees are big and strong, much sturdier than the rather anemic ones I looked at on the south shore of Lake Erie.
column185: The forest owners in my area are clearing vast swathes of soft maple swamp to grow corn on it to produce ethanol.  Leeds County dairy farmers have a unique perspective on the environment.  With DSV and wild parsnip in their ditches, if it doesn't cost them money, they ignore it.

Our woodlands are on shallow loam soils over limestone bedrock and are prone to droughts. 
We have lived here for approximately 25 years, and although this area is described as a 'low wind' area, we have experienced 2 tornadoes and a microburst in this time. We had to harvest a section of damaged trees 10 years earlier than planned (selective harvest) due to significant damage to tops.
